Dear Collinsville Volleyball Parents and Fans,

I want to relay information to you from the District 16 Volleyball Executive Committee regarding player and fan safety measures that will be enforced at all district volleyball matches related to COVID-19.

All fans ten years of age and older are required to wear a face covering upon entry into the facility per UIL guidelines.

Exceptions Include:
‚Ä¢ Any person with a medical condition or disability that prevents wearing a face covering.
‚Ä¢ While a person is consuming food or drink.
‚Ä¢ At least 6 feet of social distancing from anyone not in your household; or
‚Ä¢ Any other reason or circumstance indicated under Executive Order GA-29.

Mark Dykes
Superintendent

post_text:
Did you know Flag Day has a link to education?

Bernard Cigrand was a Wisconsin teacher and dentist. He started the idea for an annual flag day to be celebrated across the country every June 14, in 1885.

Bernard promoted the idea for years. He picked June 14th, the same day the Second Continental Congress issued the specifics for the first "American" flag.

It wasn't until 1916 that President Woodrow Wilson officially established June 14 as Flag Day.

Congratulations Mrs. Smith! üéâ
Texas Retired Teachers Foundation (TRTF) Classroom Assistance Grant announced the 30 grant winners for the 2020-2021 year! Recipients were awarded a $500.00 check from TRTF for their classroom projects. Mrs. Smith is one of the recipients and teaches 10th and 11th grade Chemistry and Physics at Collinsville High School. Her project will use a ripple tank to allow her students to generate waves and observe diffraction and interference phenomena which can only be explained by the wave theory of light. She will use her funds to purchase the tank, a DC power supply, and other supplies. Congratulations!!

post_text:
Congratulations to the CHS Class of 2020 Salutatorian, Katelyn Claytor!

Throughout High School, Katy served as an active member of FCCLA, NHS, Student Council and as the Class President all four years of school. Katy led her teams in volleyball, basketball and softball and has accomplished numerous accolades, both academically and athletically. She has served in various ways in the community, including her favorite experience, volunteering at Wilson N Jones. Katy has been accepted into the prestigious Honors Scholar Program at Texas Woman‚Äôs University. She plans to earn her Master‚Äôs in Nursing.

Congratulations Katelyn Claytor!

post_text:
Congratulations to the CHS Class of 2020 Valedictorian, Kaitlyn Rodriguez!

As a high school student, Kaitlyn, ‚ÄúKiki‚Äù served as an active member of NHS, Student Council and FCCLA. In each of these clubs she held the position of president. Her leadership is impressive and her willingness to serve is endless. Academically, Kaitlyn filled her schedule with advanced classes and participated in several UIL events such as, One Act Play, Copy Editing, and Theatrical Design.

Kaitlyn plans to attend Abilene Christian University this fall, where she will study Environmental Sciences that will lead to a career that focuses on sustainability and conservation.

Congratulations, Kaitlyn Rodriguez!

Juniors and Seniors that want to take Dual Credit in the Fall, please click the link:

https://www.grayson.edu/dual-credit/applying.html and follow the instructions.

If you have never taken dual credit before, you need to apply to Grayson, FIRST. If you took dual credit last year, you DO NOT have to reapply, just fill out the permission form. Then print out a permission form, fill it out and return it to Mrs. Baggs at the High School.

If you have questions, you can call Mrs. Baggs at (903)429-6164 or email her at melissa.baggs@collinsvilleisd.org.

April 20, 2020

CISD SCHOOL CLOSURE ANNOUNCEMENT FROM SUPERINTENDENT MARK DYKES

Today Governor Greg Abbott ordered all Texas schools to remain closed for the remained of the 2019-20 school year. CISD will abide by the Governor‚Äôs orders and has plans in place to continue meeting the educational and nutritional needs of our students.

We will continue the remote learning model that has been implemented over the past several weeks. CISD will also continue to provide two meals a day through the remainder of the school year.

I want to thank the staff for the amazing job they are doing in providing at home lessons for all our students. I also want to thank the parents for their patience and support through this unprecedented time.
text:
April 20, 2020

CISD SCHOOL CLOSURE ANNOUNCEMENT FROM SUPERINTENDENT MARK DYKES

Today Governor Greg Abbott ordered all Texas schools to remain closed for the remained of the 2019-20 school year. CISD will abide by the Governor‚Äôs orders and has plans in place to continue meeting the educational and nutritional needs of our students.

We will continue the remote learning model that has been implemented over the past several weeks. CISD will also continue to provide two meals a day through the remainder of the school year.

I want to thank the staff for the amazing job they are doing in providing at home lessons for all our students. I also want to thank the parents for their patience and support through this unprecedented time.

From CISD Food Services:

Today you are receiving 3 bags of food/milk. Two bags, need to be refrigerated. One bag does not require refrigeration. The applesauce cups are shelf stable.

All food items are precooked and some just need to be reheated before eating, this can be done in the microwave or oven.

Suggested menu:
Day
Breakfast
Lunch
Instructions
Monday
Cereal, juice, milk
Turkey/Cheese Sandwich, applesauce cup, orange, graham crackers, milk
Nothing needs to be heated.
Tuesday
Muffins, juice, milk
Burrito, chips, apple, milk
Warm burrito per package instructions.
Wednesday
French toast, juice, milk
Breaded chicken sandwich, orange, applesauce cup, goldfish, milk
French toast minis can be warmed. Chicken patty needs to be warmed.
Thursday
Cereal, juice, milk
Hamburger, apple, milk
Burger patty needs to be warmed

Thank you for allowing us to continue feeding our students.

This institution is an equal opportunity provider.

CES Teacher Parade beginning Thursday at 4pm. We will begin a drive through town starting on Northeast side near the high school. We will head south from there, winding our way northward. From there we will cross the railroad tracks on the north side and town and head south again.
We plan to follow Mr. Woody‚Äôs bus route and then go east and follow Mr. Wagner‚Äôs route.
Parents be on the lookout for us, but remember we are practicing social distancing by not stopping!
We will try to update you as we finish each part of town.
Hope to see some happy faces out there!
Please share!!

"We, therefore, the delegates with plenary powers of the people of Texas, in solemn convention assembled, appealing to a candid world for the necessities of our condition, do hereby resolve and declare, that our political connection with the Mexican nation has forever ended, and that the people of Texas do now constitute a free, Sovereign, and independent republic, and are fully invested with all the rights and attributes which properly belong to independent nations; and, conscious of the rectitude of our intentions, we fearlessly and confidently commit the issue to the decision of the Supreme arbiter of the destinies of nations."

Collinsville Athletics
February 14 at 3:06 PM ¬∑

The Lady Pirate Power Lifting team competed in the Howe invitational Thursday night and scored some impressive results, including 1st place as a team in the small-schools division! Olivia Trevino scored personal records and boasted a 200 lb bench press, taking 2nd place! Talon Andrews lifted a 310 lb squat, also taking 3rd. Lexi Roberts scored a 350 lb squat, taking 2nd. Ashlee Bacher took 4th. Kylie Johnson also took 5th. Camryn Hickman took 4th place as well. Jessica McAdams took 6th with a 305 lb deadlift. Makenzie Roberts, and Mekenzie Morley also scored highly. Coach Stone and Coach McAdams are very thankful for the all-star support of Cory Sheppard and Angie Aguilera as well. Way to go Pirates!

post_text:
Attention High School Parents: We are having issues with 7-12 grade students who are out of compliance with the code of conduct in regards to dress and grooming. Students will have until Wednesday morning January 22nd to be in compliance with all dress and grooming standards. For example, students needing haircuts will need to have this done by that deadline. Students who are not in compliance will face disciplinary consequences. If you have any questions please contact Daniel Bates High School Principal.

We are also having an issue with individuals who are not parents or guardians bringing food to the school for 7-12 grade students. Effective immediately, only parents or guardians may bring food for their own child or children. Thank you for your understanding. Once again if you have any questions, please contact Daniel Bates High School Principal.
